english:
  title: Preface to Eight Poems on the Eight Scenes of Ryukyu's Eternal Bliss Temple
  author: Gwon Geon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the southeastern lands dwell the nations of Japan and Ryukyu, situated beyond ten thousand leagues of churning waves and raging tides, yet separated from our realm by vast distances. Through the water roads they come and go, maintaining goodwill across generations. Ryukyu lies farthest of all, and when it cannot send envoys of its own, it entrusts its sincere regards to the ambassadors of Japan. This summer of the gengzi year, the Buddhist priest Sojo from Japan arrived bearing Ryukyu's greetings. His Highness, recognizing the virtue of this gesture, commanded the authorities to receive him with honors at the gates, extending generous provisions and hospitality. The man himself bore an air of rectitude and purity, possessed of spiritual grace, with calligraphy and verse alike worthy of admiration.

    When his business was concluded and he prepared to depart, he presented eight poems depicting the scenes of Ryukyu's Eternal Bliss Temple. These were composed by Nanpo, with verses of response sought by Cheng Wenda. I reflected: even the gentleman is called blind if he inquires of a country he has not entered and its customs he has not witnessed—how much more so can one compose of landscapes one has never beheld? Though we dwell within the same world, I remain bound to this green peninsula, and gazing upon Ryukyu is like gazing between distant Yan and far Yue—I have never once fixed my eyes upon it. How could I know the crystalline oddness of some distant mountain or temple, the serene beauty of some faraway water or hill?

    Yet Nanpo's verses are so profound and pellucid, so refined in their grace, that they capture the extraordinary splendor of Eternal Bliss nearly in full. Upon reading his poetry—reciting it with lips while the mind imagines—those eight scenes suddenly illuminate the chamber of the heart. It is as though one sits in the Moon Pavilion gazing down upon the river road, drawing water from the Tangerine Well while listening to the dawn bell, hearing woodcutter's songs echoing along the path, the wind through pines sighing at one's ears, and feeling clear breezes quicken between tooth and cheek. Need one truly tread upon strange stones and witness their intimate welcomings to create such beauty? Thus I hastily added a brief preface and gathered verses of response from several others, binding all into a single scroll to entrust to Sojo's traveling case, that Wenda might receive it. What, I wonder, will Wenda make of this? Perhaps through it he will come to know the flourishing of our nation's rituals, music, and culture; our way of befriending neighbors and drawing in distant lands; the abundance of our literary scholars and the refinement of their works. Perhaps it will deepen his understanding of our commitment to harmony and the maintenance of proper diplomatic observance.

    I am told that Ryukyu reveres learning and culture greatly. Surely among its people are those skilled in verse? Yet the fact that they do not rest content with their own accomplishment but seek our compositions—is this not worthy of note? Should all of Ryukyu's nation continue to admire our traditions and request poetry from us, even if a thousand or ten thousand sought such verses, would I dare refuse?

    —Written in the seventh month, early week of autumn, Year Sixteen of the Chenghua era

    The eight scenes are: Ten Thousand Pine Mountain, Green River Road, Guest-Farewell Bridge, Woodcutter's Song Valley, Tide-Moon Pavilion, Neighboring Temple Bell, Jade Tangerine Well, and Strange Stone Path.
  footnotes:
    - Nanpo and Cheng Wenda were likely Buddhist or literary figures associated with Ryukyu during this period of Korean-Ryukyuan cultural exchange.
    - The Chenghua era refers to the Ming Dynasty period (1465-1487), placing this preface in 1480.
    - The 'green peninsula' (靑丘) is a classical poetic name for Korea.
    - Yan and Yue are ancient regions representing the farthest north and south boundaries of the known world in classical Chinese geography, used here to emphasize extreme distance.
